  <article class="article-body">

    <p class="article-note" style="padding:12px 16px;border-radius:8px;background:#eff6ff;border:1px solid #bfdbfe;font-size:0.88rem;color:#1e40af;margin-bottom:24px;"><strong>Note:</strong> This feature was originally called "direct mode" during development. The user-facing name is <strong>solo mode</strong>, which is what you'll see in the CLI and docs.</p>

    <p>devopsellence has always been opinionated about how deploys work: agents pull desired state, reconcile containers, and report status. That loop is the same whether you're deploying to a fleet managed by the control plane or to a single VPS you SSH into. But until now, using devopsellence meant running the control plane &mdash; or at minimum, a standalone backend.</p>

    <p>Today we're shipping <strong>solo mode</strong>: deploy to any server with nothing but SSH and Docker. No control plane. No cloud services. No registry. One command, and your app is running.</p>

    <pre><code>$ devopsellence mode use solo
$ devopsellence deploy
Building image myapp:a1b2c3d ...
[prod-1] Transferring image...
[prod-1] Writing desired state...
[prod-1] Deployed a1b2c3d
Deployed revision a1b2c3d to 1 node(s)</code></pre>

    <h2>The problem</h2>

    <p>Standalone mode removed the GCP dependency. But it still requires running the control plane &mdash; a Rails app with a database, background jobs, and HTTP endpoints that agents poll for desired state and secrets. For a team deploying a single app to one or two servers, that's a lot of infrastructure to manage the infrastructure.</p>

    <p>We kept hearing the same request: "I just want to deploy to my server. I have SSH access. I don't need a dashboard or multi-tenant isolation or a registry. Can I just push my app?"</p>

    <p>Solo mode is the answer.</p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>

    <p>The architecture is deliberately simple. The CLI does all the coordination. The agent does all the reconciliation. SSH is the only transport.</p>

    <pre><code>Developer machine                           Remote node
+-----------------+                         +------------------+
| devopsellence   |  docker save | gzip     | gunzip |         |
| deploy (solo)   | ---- SSH ------------> | docker load      |
|                 |                         |                  |
|                 |  desired-state.json     | agent            |
|                 | ---- SSH ------------> | (--mode=direct)  |
|                 |                         |   |              |
|                 |                         |   v              |
|                 |  cat status.json        | reconcile loop   |
|                 | <--- SSH ------------- | -> containers    |
+-----------------+                         +------------------+</code></pre>

    <p>Three SSH operations, and you're deployed:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Transfer the image.</strong> <code>docker save</code> pipes through <code>gzip</code> over SSH to <code>docker load</code> on the remote. No registry to configure, no credentials to manage, no image tags to coordinate. The image goes directly from your machine to the server.</li>
      <li><strong>Write the desired state.</strong> The CLI builds a JSON document describing what should run &mdash; containers, env vars, secrets, health checks, volumes &mdash; and writes it to a file on the remote node via SSH. The agent watches this file.</li>
      <li><strong>Agent reconciles.</strong> The agent's 2-second loop picks up the new desired state, finds the pre-loaded image locally, starts the container, runs health checks, updates Envoy, drains the old container. Zero-downtime rollout, same as always.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>The agent in solo mode</h2>

    <p>The agent already knew how to read desired state from a local file &mdash; the override mechanism existed for debugging. Solo mode makes that the primary authority.</p>

    <p>When started with the solo-path implementation flag <code>--mode=direct</code>, the agent skips everything related to the control plane: no auth manager, no GCP credentials, no remote desired-state fetching, no secret resolution, no diagnostics reporting. What's left is the core: a file-watching authority, the reconciler, and a local status reporter.</p>

    <pre><code># On the remote node
devopsellence --mode=direct \
  --auth-state-path=/var/lib/devopsellence/state.json</code></pre>

    <p>The file-watching authority uses filesystem metadata (mtime and size) for change detection. When the desired-state file hasn't changed, the fetch is a single <code>stat</code> call. When it has, the authority parses the JSON and returns the new state to the reconciler. No polling an HTTP endpoint, no conditional ETags &mdash; just the filesystem.</p>

    <p>Secret resolution is eliminated entirely. In shared mode, the agent resolves secret references at fetch time by calling Secret Manager or the control plane. In solo mode, the CLI pre-resolves all secrets and writes them as plain environment variables in the desired-state JSON. The agent sees final values, not references.</p>

    <p>Image pulling is eliminated too. <code>ImagePullAuth</code> is nil. The reconciler's <code>ensureImage</code> method checks <code>ImageExists</code> first and only attempts a pull if the image isn't found locally. Since the CLI pre-loads images via <code>docker save/load</code>, they're always found locally. No registry auth, no pull credentials, no network calls.</p>

    <h2>The image transfer pipeline</h2>

    <p>Transferring Docker images over SSH without a registry is the kind of thing that sounds straightforward until you implement it. The naive approach &mdash; save to a file, scp, load &mdash; requires 3x the disk space (local tarball, remote tarball, extracted layers). The streaming approach pipes everything through without intermediate files:</p>

    <pre><code>docker save myapp:a1b2c3d | gzip | ssh deploy@host 'gunzip | docker load'</code></pre>

    <p>In Go, this means wiring three processes together with pipes:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><code>docker save</code> writes to a pipe</li>
      <li><code>gzip</code> reads from that pipe, writes to another pipe</li>
      <li>SSH reads from the second pipe, streams to the remote <code>docker load</code></li>
    </ol>

    <p>The tricky part is failure handling. If SSH fails (auth error, network timeout), the gzip process is still writing to a pipe that nobody is reading. It blocks. Docker save is still writing to gzip. The whole pipeline hangs until the context timeout kills it. The fix: when SSH returns an error, close the read end of the pipe with the error. This unblocks gzip's writes, which cascades to unblock docker save. The pipeline tears down cleanly in milliseconds instead of hanging for minutes.</p>

    <h2>Secrets without a secret manager</h2>

    <p>Solo mode stores secrets in a local <code>.devopsellence/secrets.env</code> file in the workspace root:</p>

    <pre><code>$ devopsellence secret set DATABASE_URL --value postgres://localhost/mydb
Secret "DATABASE_URL" saved

$ devopsellence secret set API_KEY --value sk-live-abc123
Secret "API_KEY" saved

$ devopsellence secret list
API_KEY
DATABASE_URL</code></pre>

    <p>The file format is standard <code>.env</code> &mdash; one <code>KEY=VALUE</code> per line, with support for comments, quoting, and the <code>export</code> prefix. File permissions are set to <code>0600</code>.</p>

    <p>During deploy, the CLI loads this file, resolves each <code>secret_refs</code> entry in <code>devopsellence.yml</code> against the local secrets, and merges them into the desired-state JSON as plain env vars. If any referenced secret is missing, the deploy fails immediately with a clear message telling you which secrets to add. No silent partial deploys.</p>

    <p>This is the right trade-off for solo mode. You don't get IAM-scoped access, key rotation, or audit logging. You get a file on your machine that you can manage with your existing secrets workflow &mdash; pass it in CI, encrypt it with git-crypt, pull it from Vault, or just keep it in <code>.gitignore</code>.</p>

    <h2>Configuration</h2>

    <p>Solo mode configuration lives in the same <code>devopsellence.yml</code> that defines your app. Today it is stored under the <code>direct</code> block:</p>

    <pre><code>schema_version: 3
organization: my-org
project: my-app

build:
  context: .
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

web:
  command: "./server"
  port: 3000
  healthcheck:
    path: /up
    port: 3000
  env:
    RAILS_ENV: production
  secret_refs:
    - name: DATABASE_URL
      secret: ignored-in-direct-mode

direct:
  nodes:
    prod-1:
      host: 10.0.0.5
      user: deploy
    prod-2:
      host: 10.0.0.6
      user: deploy
      ssh_key: ~/.ssh/deploy_ed25519</code></pre>

    <p>Each node specifies a host, user, and optionally a port, SSH key, and agent state directory. The defaults are sensible: port 22, state in <code>/var/lib/devopsellence</code>.</p>

    <p>Deploy to all nodes, or target specific ones:</p>

    <pre><code># Deploy to all configured nodes
$ devopsellence deploy

# Deploy to specific nodes only
$ devopsellence deploy --nodes prod-1

# Check status
$ devopsellence status

# Tail logs
$ devopsellence node logs prod-1 --follow</code></pre>

    <p>Targeting a node that doesn't exist in the config is an immediate error, not a silent no-op. Typos don't cause partial deploys.</p>

    <h2>What stays the same</h2>

    <p>Solo mode changes how state reaches the agent. It doesn't change what the agent does with it. The reconciliation loop is identical:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Zero-downtime deploys.</strong> New container starts, passes health checks, gets added to Envoy's endpoint list. Old container drains, then stops. Same choreography as control-plane mode.</li>
      <li><strong>Health checking.</strong> HTTP probes against the configured path and port. The container isn't routed to until it's healthy.</li>
      <li><strong>Envoy integration.</strong> Traffic routing via xDS endpoint discovery. The agent updates Envoy's config atomically.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain delays.</strong> Configurable delay between removing the old endpoint and stopping the old container, so in-flight requests complete.</li>
      <li><strong>Self-healing.</strong> If a container crashes, the next reconciliation loop restarts it. The 2-second loop means recovery is fast.</li>
      <li><strong>Release commands.</strong> Run once per deploy before container swap &mdash; database migrations, asset compilation, cache warming.</li>
      <li><strong>Volume mounts.</strong> Persistent data survives container replacement.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>You don't give up deploy safety by skipping the control plane. The safety properties come from the reconciliation loop, not from the transport layer.</p>

    <h2>The spectrum</h2>

    <p>devopsellence now offers three deployment backends, each making a different trade-off between simplicity and capability:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th></th>
          <th>Solo</th>
          <th>Standalone</th>
          <th>GCP</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Control plane</strong></td>
          <td>None</td>
          <td>Self-hosted</td>
          <td>Self-hosted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Image delivery</strong></td>
          <td>SSH pipe</td>
          <td>Any OCI registry</td>
          <td>Artifact Registry</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Secret storage</strong></td>
          <td>Local .env file</td>
          <td>Encrypted database</td>
          <td>Secret Manager</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Desired state</strong></td>
          <td>File on node</td>
          <td>Control plane API</td>
          <td>Cloud Storage</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Identity</strong></td>
          <td>SSH keypair</td>
          <td>Bearer token</td>
          <td>Workload Identity</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Multi-node</strong></td>
          <td>Parallel SSH</td>
          <td>Per-node polling</td>
          <td>Per-node polling</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Best for</strong></td>
          <td>1&ndash;5 nodes, single app</td>
          <td>Small fleet, self-hosted</td>
          <td>Production fleet</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>Start with solo mode when you have a server and an app. Move to standalone when you need a dashboard, multi-environment management, or automated node provisioning. Move to GCP when you need HSM-backed signing, IAM-scoped secrets, and managed identity federation.</p>

    <p>The migration path is smooth because the agent reconciliation loop &mdash; the part that actually runs your app &mdash; is the same in all three modes. What changes is how desired state and secrets get to the agent, not what happens after they arrive.</p>

    <h2>What shipped</h2>

    <p>Solo mode touches the agent and CLI without changing the control plane:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Agent:</strong> internal <code>--mode=direct</code> flag, file-watching authority with mtime-based change detection, simplified startup that skips auth/GCP/control-plane wiring</li>
      <li><strong>CLI:</strong> shared root verbs with <code>devopsellence mode use solo</code>, then <code>deploy</code>, <code>status</code>, <code>secret</code>, and <code>node logs</code></li>
      <li><strong>Config:</strong> <code>direct.nodes</code> section in <code>devopsellence.yml</code> with per-node SSH settings</li>
      <li><strong>Tests:</strong> unit tests for desired-state building, secret management, config validation; end-to-end test that spins up a Docker-based SSH node with the solo-path agent, deploys an app via the CLI, and verifies the full lifecycle</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The existing control-plane and standalone paths are unchanged. Every existing test passes.</p>

    <hr>

    <p>If you want to understand the reconciliation loop that solo mode shares with every other deployment backend, read the <strong><%= link_to "Engineering Decisions series", blog_post_path(slug: "engineering-decisions-part-1-pull-not-push") %></strong>. If you want to understand how standalone mode made the control plane self-sufficient without GCP, read <strong><%= link_to "Standalone mode: from GCP-only to run-anywhere", blog_post_path(slug: "standalone-mode-from-gcp-only-to-run-anywhere") %></strong>.</p>

